Anti-globalization backlash.
A palpable sense of unease was felt during the G-7 summit at Ise-Shima in Japan.
At the next gathering of world leaders from developed economies, none can say which of them will be among the populist insurgents.
The president Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with the British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, the Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with the German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could make themselves the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has been ongoing for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend apparently was convergence and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has illustrated this kind of globalization: breaking into stores from this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the character of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Despite the world becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a sense that we understand foreigners less and less.
In response to the evolving preferences of consumers (which are becoming increasingly nuanced), companies are relocating their production closer to markets where their goods will be sold.
This undermines the growth of international trade.
This is not a new trend.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began to produce these cars domestically.
Currently, most "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are made in the United States. But the reversal of the globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of technologies like 3D printing.
Thus the current criticism of globalization tends to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution does not only reflect the slowdown in the growth of trade.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases, even dependent on them, since the constantly updated electronics and the affordable "fast fashion" that has become dominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on opaque courts that protect the interests of foreign companies and are perceived to infringe on national sovereignty.
The global refugee crisis is next: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a harbinger of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why do people in developed countries fear foreigners so much?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures before.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to far-off destinations and hundreds of millions of people from around the world head to developed countries every year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we have a greater tendency to experience things superficially and quickly, rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches, a unique interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper foundation of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous contact is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are not inclined to provide good or even honest service to people who will certainly never come back.
Restaurants serve up mediocre (or worse) food with a scowl, taxi drivers scam you, and hoteliers lie about their facilities.
In addition, this little game can be disrupted.
On the sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it has also become a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
A few attacks in places like Bali or Red Sea resort complexes are enough to trigger a profound economic destabilization.
To minimize contact with local populations, tourism companies respond to such risks.
The emblem of modern tourism is a massive cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (visiting a stunning Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship, Harmony of the Seas, aims to recreate all the world's climates.
The ship, which is longer than the Eiffel Tower, boasts a tropical park, an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourism companies operating buses or trains take similar precautions to ensure the safety of their clients, releasing them on a famous site for only a limited time, in fact, just long enough to take a few photos.
This type of travel imposes constraints on the capacity of local infrastructure.
We often lack space to stroll along the canals of Venice or along the path leading to the Acropolis.
This superficial approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stick to the confines of their pre-planned excursions, encountering only scammers who offer them trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
The locals don't much care for tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
Nobody feels particularly invested, nor does anyone maintain any trust relationships.
We often find ourselves nostalgic for the time when tourism went hand-in-hand with extended stays and meaningful encounters with vastly different cultures.
It would be obviously impossible, for the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months on end in ancient monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for instance, can offer a much more engaging experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
World leaders could they participate in summits like the G-7, by living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country ?
Not long after the United States' entry into World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of packing up and moving into the White House for 24 days, in order to consolidate the transatlantic alliance of Great Britain, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity might well be the greatest enemy of current anti-globalization populists.
